Feature Creation Notebook for Uda ML Nanodegree Capstone Project¶

The goal of this notebook is to load the datasets that are suggested in the project report, and manipulate them with the goal to produce a bidders_new.csv.

Exploring the datasets¶

First will import the libraries involved and load the data. Datasets that are saved in datasets kaggle file and can be found here for quickload are:

  • datasets kaggle/human_robot/bids.csv
  • datasets kaggle/human_robot/train.csv
  • datasets kaggle/human_robot/test.csv
  • datasets kaggle/human_robot/sampleSubmission.csv

Understanding the datasets¶

The two datasets above are not really features that can go through a pre-processing step and then thrown straight into a classifier. Instead, from these datasets we first need to extract features. However, prior to that we also need to understand the raw datasets.

Exploring bidders dataset¶

For that, a first step, to understand the bidders dataset will be to:

  • Identify how many unique bidders we have,
  • how many bidding accounts,
  • how many bidding adresses,
  • the extend these are mixxed up, meaning that there are accounts or addresses that belong to more than one users.

Exploring bids dataset¶

Now as far as the auctions dataset goes, the aim is to understand:

  • How many bids there are made,
  • how many unique bidders participate,
  • how many unique auctions there are,
  • how many unique merchandise categories are included,
  • how many unique devices are used,
  • from how many unique countries the bids are,
  • how many unique ips the bids are coming from,
  • how many unique urls are being used.

Interpretation: Many things could be said from this computations. First of all it seems that this file is pretty large with more than 7.5 million rows, but that is expected given that a single user should be able to generate thousands of bids. It also seems that every bid is unique and there are no duplicates.

An interesting thing about the unique bidders in this dataset is that the number of unique bidders is 6614 which is 4601 less than the bidders dataset. That is because originally , in the competition, a test set is also given with 4700 bidder ids. This set will not be used here because they used it for evaluation and it is not labeled. The way i dealt with this here, is by droping the rows in the bids dataset that do not correspond to our working bidder ids in the bidders table. That will also limit the computation load for this project to a more realistic timescale.

In addition to that, in the dataset there are 15051 auctions, 7351 unique devices and only 10 categories. This means that there are probably a great deal of observations by every bidder in those categories. Finally, there are around 2.3 million ips and 1.78 million urls that the auctions originate from. This means that one or more bidders might have used plenty of those over time.

Plotting the bids dataset¶

To get a more intuitive understanding of the dataset, in the next cell i am running a check on whether it is sorted in an ascending fashion according to the time column or not, and then plotting the timestamps to check their distribution (if sorted then it should be a straight line).

The time is obfuscated and it seems to be in a unix-like format, meaning that it is an integer starting from a point and incremented since then.

In [4]:
# plotting a figure for all 7m+ ids including the ones that do not exist
import matplotlib as mpl

# style
plt.style.use('bmh')

def plot_the_timeseries(ts, bb=20):

    # init the figure and the axes object
    fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(1, 2)
    fig.set_tight_layout(False)
    #print(fig.get_figwidth())
    #print(fig.get_figheight())

    # adjust the size of the figure
    fig.set_figwidth(12)
    fig.set_figheight(6)
    # plot
    ax1.plot(ts[:bb], '-o', linewidth=0.5, markersize=5)#markeredgewidth=0.1, 
    ax2.plot(ts, '-', linewidth=1, markersize=1)#markeredgewidth=0.1,
    # set text axes 1
    ax1.set_title('Timescale of first {} Bids\n'.format(bb))
    ax1.set_xlabel('bids')
    ax1.set_ylabel('time')
    # set text axes 2
    ax2.set_title('Overall Timescale of Bids\n')
    ax2.set_xlabel('bids')
    ax2.set_ylabel('time')
    # get the labels to rotate them
    labels1 = ax1.get_xticklabels()
    labels2 = ax2.get_xticklabels()
    # rotate
    plt.setp(labels1, rotation=45, horizontalalignment='right')
    plt.setp(labels2, rotation=45, horizontalalignment='right')
    # show
    plt.show()

# plot the the timeseries
plot_the_timeseries(data_bids['time'])

Interpretation: From the second plot, the Overall Timescale of Bids it is evident that there are 3 trends that are seemingly monotonic as their value increases or remains stable. By looking closer at the first 20 bids, it seems that the way they increment is by batches (probably due to the refresh rate of the auctions website, that might be sampling at a given frequency). The latter means that in a given timestamp there might be several bids.

Monotony check¶

A next step after shortening is to bring the dataset into a useful monotonic order. But just before stepping into this it is worth running a check as to what extend is the timeseries in ascending order. From the plot earlier, we can see that there is a point at around index 2.3m where there is a drop in value. There the monotony breaks it is obvious. But there might be subtleties that are not becoming visible by the overall graph. In order to do that i will run a check in the next cell* **.

* I did run the check with a lot of trial and error and came up with the one index of the one visible monotony break. There was no need for a more complex function since it was easy to find it that way and that in the end there were no other subtle breaks.

** The index is much smaller than around the 2.3m mark because the data frame is shortened.

Transforming the bids dataset¶

According to how the dataset looks like so far, there are probably two more things that would be useful to be done to it; these are:

  1. To sort it properly according to the time column (so that time is always ascending),
  2. to normalize the time so that it starts from 0 and*,
  3. to readjust the index so that there are no "holes" to it like we see in the helper series where many indices have Nan when plotted.

As far as the first point is concerned, it is needed for when we create tables for features later on which will be ordered from the get go and they will not need to be sorted again. Also, by normalizing it is easier to understand the timeseries (how it increments etc.) since the numbers will be shorter - this ordering doesn't make sense anyway as it is since it is transformed to protect privacy. Finally by normalizing plotting is being made easier and also understanding the data easier when looking at a clipped table. The original id will be kept in bid_id but it is not needed anyway.

thing to do at the dataset before creating the features would be to reduce its time column to start from 0. In order to do that i will find the lowest value and subtract it from all values so that the lowest value (that should be at index 0*), is itself 0. The reason to do this, is that it becomes a little bit more readable (less digits), and more easy to plot and see changes (starting from 0). This time series anyway does not make any sense since to protect privacy the time data is itself transformed in the first place - in terms of time.

* In order to do that i will find the lowest value and subtract it from all values so that the lowest value (that should be at index 0), is itself 0.

Shortening the bidders and bids dataset by dropping not needed columns¶

In addition to these processes and the rows shortening on the bids dataset for this project the bid_id columns is not useful so i will drop it here. This might be a foreign key to allow indexing on other tables but for this project it is not needed.

The bidders dataset also seems to have some useless columns. As seen earlier, all e-mail addresses and payment account are unique, and they are also obfuscated to protect privacy. They do not seem to offer anything to a learner. I will also drop them here.

Shortening the bidders and bids dataset further¶

Besides dropping the bid ids for bids set, and the addresses and payment accounts for the bidders set, another idea would be to drop the bidders (and their corresponding bids) for whom we have very little information. For example if there is a bidder for whom we have 0 or only 2-3 bids, that is very little information to make an inference, except if there is a super-human unique characteristic, like betting extremely fast, which is a good enough predictor.

For that reason i think it would make sense if i alter the problem a little bit and try to build a classifier only for when there is already some basic history.

In addition to that i will also run a check for whether the new tables that are being made with such a function are monotonic, because i will construct them in such a way later on and i'd rather not lose time on that.

number_of_bids = 20

np.set_printoptions(threshold=4)

# maybe make dict comprehension
d = {k: v for (k, v) in zip(np.arange(number_of_bids),
                            [np.array([]) for x in np.arange(number_of_bids)])}

# find users names with 0 bids that will not appear in groupby
d[0] = data_bidders['bidder_id'][~data_bidders['bidder_id'].isin(data_bids['bidder_id'])].values

for bidder_id, group in data_bids.groupby('bidder_id'):
    
    if group.shape[0]<number_of_bids:
        idx = group.shape[0]
        d[idx] = np.append(d[idx], bidder_id)
        
    # check if the new dataframe is sorted by the columns and throw a ValueError if not
    mono_check_bidders = group['time'].is_monotonic
    
    if not mono_check_bidders:
        print("Warning! Bidder id '{}' does not have sorted bidder table! Sorting is needed.."
              .format(bidder_id))
    
for k, v in d.items():
    print("The {} bidders with {} entries are:{}\n".format(len(v), k, v))

# Find the unique bidders
print("There are {} bidders with {} or more bids."
      .format(np.sum([len(x) for x in d.values()]), number_of_bids))

Interpretation: It seems that there are only 7 cases of bots in 1041 bidders (which is more than half of the dataset). The ratio from 95% humans and 5% bots drops to 99.33% humans and 0.67% bots. One reason for that might be that for those users it is too early to decide, and that the issuing authority has missed some of them (it is also stated in the description that there is noise in the labels). It might be a good idea to get rid of those bidders; for example the ones that have 10 or less bids.   5. As far as ips are concerned this dimension seems to have the distribution with the largest values.   6. Finally urls go, it also follows the same pattern with left skeweness as its median is 446.65 while the median is only 10. That means there are crazy outliers, which can also be seen from its std, which might be less than the ip case but still in the crazy large ballpark.

Feature Making¶

In the next few sections we will inspect more closely each column of the bids set and we will try use it to make features. From the abose section we already have a clue for what to expect in every column. Also, after inspecting there will be a discussion for the features we will be using and a function implementation that will extract them.

Time column - Finding the big steps and normalizing with a unit of time¶

The first (and maybe most important column that we do features with is time. So far we did some exploring in terms of the timeseries which was a bit generic. We saw how the overall series plots, then we sorted the entire bids set according to it and finally we made it start from 0.

Another thing we could do with the time column could be to try bring it closer to our perception of time as well as to find the two really big steps and their indices. The latter could probably help when making features, and it would give us an understanding as to how big of a step it is relative to the smallest step which we can count as a unit of time. In the next cell we will:

  • Find all the unique timestamps in the timseries
  • Test whether the first recorded step between the the 6th and 7th index in the bids dataframe is what happens in the rest of the series (if lets say the auctions site has a steady sampling rate)
In [18]:
# Find the unique timestamps
time_series_values = np.unique(data_bids['time'])

# Get the number of unique timestamps
num_unique_timestamps = len(time_series_values)

print("There are {} unique timestamps.\n".format(num_unique_timestamps))

steps = []

step = 52631579

for i, t in enumerate(list(time_series_values[1:])):
    # increment the previous timestamp with what presumably is one unit of time
    expected_t = time_series_values[i] + step
    # get the difference of the two timestamps 
    real_expected_diff = t - expected_t
    # add it to steps
    steps.append(real_expected_diff+step)

# put the leaps into a Series
steps_series = pd.Series(steps).value_counts()

num_non_unit_step_values = num_unique_timestamps - steps_series.iloc[0]

print("The number of steps that are exactly 52631579 are {}. Only the {:.2f}% of the total steps \
were not of the 52631579 magnitude.\n"
      .format(steps_series.iloc[0], num_non_unit_step_values/steps_series.iloc[0]*100))

print("Here are the counts for every step:\n{}".format(steps_series))

Interpretation: First of all regarding the unique timestamps, out of the around 3m rows there are around 743k unique timestamps, which means that there are a lot of ids recorded in the same timestamps as others. Also, as far as the first recorded step goes - which happens at the index 6 to 7 in the bids set and is exactly 52631579 - it seems that it appears in around 673k of the 743k steps (that is around 90% of the time), and in around 37k steps the step magnitude is just 1 shorter than 52631579. That makes us think that probaly the most realistic unit of time would be something like 52631578.95.

However 52631579 is good enough as a normalization number, since what we ultimately want is to reduce the timeseries into a more comprehensible series and to identify the indices of the two big steps which will happen in the next cell. Finally, it also needs to be said, that the remaining 10% of the steps that are not 52631579 are multipliers of that (and if not exact multipliers very close ones), so it seems that while there was a steady sampling frequency by the auction site sometimes some samples were missed. The maximum step except the crazy ones is 526315790, which happens only once and is only 10 times bigger than 52631579 that is presumably the sampling rate.

# find the largest step
largest_step = np.max(steps)

big_step_indices = []

for i, t in enumerate(data_bids['time'][1:]):
    # get the difference of the two timestamps 
    real_expected_diff = t - data_bids['time'][i]
    # test if this is one of the two cases
    if real_expected_diff == largest_step:
        big_step_indices.append((i, i+1))

Features to be made with time column¶

Probably the best features for this project will be the ones that closely relate to time. That is because a bot will probably have a strategy on how to bid and it does not think or behaves randomly like a human which calls for a prolonged response in chaotic-like patterns.

From all the analysis of the timeseries we have so far made, it seems like the auctions platform has three biding periods that probably accounts for three days or three weeks or something like that. The main way to produce features from it would be by taking the timeseries and computing:

  • the number of unique bids
  • the ratio of simultaneous bids to all bids
  • the timestamp of the earlies bid someone made (min)
  • the timestamp of the latest bid someone made (max)
  • the timestamp of the middle bid someone made (median)
  • the mean timestamp of someone's bids (mean)
  • the variance in timestamps of someones bids (std)

In addition to that there is a case to be made for the intervals, which capture the frequency with which someone bids. As far as intervals are concerned there are similar features we can build according to them:

  • the number of periods someone participated in (did he participate in all periods/days/weeks?)
  • the smallest interval (min)
  • the biggest interval (max)
  • the median interval (median)
  • the mean interval (mean)
  • the variance of intervals (std)

def descriptive_stats(series):
    """ Takes a distribution and computes several descriptive statistic functions. """
    return np.min(series), np.max(series), np.median(series), np.mean(series), np.std(series)


def features_timeseries_simple(series, huge_gap_in_time, smaller_table=False):
    """ Produces 13 features for a timseries. The 7 first have to do with the timeseries,
    and the following 6 with a series of intervals from the timeseries."""
    
    # number of bids
    num_bids = series.shape[0]
    
    # find the ratio of how many bids did not happen simultaneously relative to all bids
    simultaneous_bid_ratio = 1 - (np.unique(series).shape[0] / series.shape[0])
    
    # find earliest bid of the user
    earliest_bid = np.min(series)
    
    # find latest bid of the user
    latest_bid = np.max(series)
    
    # find the timestamp of the bid in the middle
    middle_bid = np.median(series)
    
    # find the mean bid timestamp
    mean_bid_timestamp = np.mean(series)
    
    # find the std of the timestamp
    std_bid_timestamp = np.std(series)
    
    ######### Move on to the intervals stats #########
    
    # get the intervals between the timestamps
    intervals = series.sub(series.shift(1))
    
    # reduce the intervals shape
    intervals = intervals[1:] if intervals.shape[0] > 1 else intervals
        
    # find at which of the 3 periods a user participated in by the 2 possible gaps in time
    num_periods_participated_in = np.count_nonzero(intervals > huge_gap_in_time) + 1

    # remove those values
    intervals = intervals[intervals < huge_gap_in_time]
    
    if intervals.shape[0] > 1:
        
        # find the smallest interval
        smallest_interval = np.min(intervals)
    
        # find the biggest interval
        largest_interval = np.max(intervals)
    
        # find the median of the intervals
        median_intervals = np.median(intervals)
    
        # find the mean of the intervals
        mean_intervals = np.mean(intervals)
        
        # find the std of the intervals
        std_intervals = np.std(intervals)
        
    elif intervals.shape[0] <= 1 and not smaller_table:
        
        # set them as nan and filter them out later as rows
        smallest_interval, largest_interval, median_intervals, mean_intervals, std_intervals = \
        None, None, None, None, None
        
    else:
        
        # set them 0 as they will get filtered out 
        smallest_interval, largest_interval, median_intervals, mean_intervals, std_intervals = \
        0, 0, 0, 0, 0
        
    return num_bids, simultaneous_bid_ratio, earliest_bid, latest_bid, middle_bid,\
            mean_bid_timestamp, std_bid_timestamp, num_periods_participated_in, smallest_interval,\
            largest_interval, median_intervals, mean_intervals, std_intervals

Features to be made with time column and a grouping by unique ids of another column¶

In addition to those features that relate to time, suspicious timeseries patters might arise by bidders according to the auction they are betting on, or the country they are betting from. In order to capture that, we need to examine the timeseries in a case to case basis (e.g. auction to auction) and then we will have a distribution of for example, mins, maxs, means, medians etc. for each case. At these distributions we can also try find descriptive statistics, for example if we have a distribution of all means in the auctions a bidder participated in, we can then take some descriptive statistics for a distribuitions of lets say mins:

  • the min of all mins,
  • the max of all mins,
  • the median of all mins,
  • the mean of all mins,
  • and the std of all mins,

and we can do the same thing for all 13 features we extract from a timeseries for which we will have distributions from.

That suggests that all 13 features for a timeseries that we discuss above can be applied to the case by case basis which will result into a distribution of each one of them. However, since we talked about 5 descriptive statistics of those distributions, and there are will be 13 of them, we are making the feature space explode as that accouns for 65 features, and if we run it with all categories, it would account for $65*6=390$ features. This could be counterable to an extend with some feature selection later on, or some robust algorithm to overfit like RF and long training time. In addition to that we might not run it with every category, because given what we have seen from merchandise category or ips and urls there is probably less meaningful to run it there.

def features_time_with_grouping(df, second_category, huge_gap_in_time):
    """ Produces 65 features for multiple timeseries that can be found by grouping the bids of a
    bidder by categories like 'auction' or 'country'."""
    
    # initialize arrays for timeseries base stats
    num_bids = np.array([])
    rat_sim_bids = np.array([])
    series_mins = np.array([])
    series_maxs = np.array([])
    series_medians = np.array([])
    series_means = np.array([])
    series_stds = np.array([])
    
    # initialize arrays for interval base stats
    num_periods = np.array([])
    intervals_mins = np.array([])
    intervals_maxs = np.array([])
    intervals_medians = np.array([])
    intervals_means = np.array([])
    intervals_stds = np.array([])
    
    # group the dataframe by auctions
    for _, group in df.groupby(second_category):
        
        # 13 features for the standalone timeseries of a user
        a, b, c, d, e, f, g, aa, bb, cc, dd, ee, ff = \
        features_timeseries_simple(group['time'], huge_gap_in_time, smaller_table=True)
        
        # append timseries stats
        num_bids = np.append(num_bids, a)
        rat_sim_bids = np.append(rat_sim_bids, b)
        series_mins = np.append(series_mins, c)
        series_maxs = np.append(series_maxs, d)
        series_medians = np.append(series_medians, e)
        series_means = np.append(series_means, f)
        series_stds = np.append(series_stds, g)
        
        # append intervals stats
        num_periods = np.append(num_periods, aa)
        intervals_mins = np.append(intervals_mins, bb)
        intervals_maxs = np.append(intervals_maxs, cc)
        intervals_medians = np.append(intervals_medians, dd)
        intervals_means = np.append(intervals_means, ee)
        intervals_stds = np.append(intervals_stds, ff)
            
    # check how many zeros are in the array
    count_zeros = np.count_nonzero(intervals_means==0)
    
    if count_zeros and count_zeros!=intervals_means.shape[0]:
        # find the indices of all other numbers
        indices = np.where(intervals_means!=0)
        intervals_mins = intervals_mins[indices]
        intervals_maxs = intervals_maxs[indices]
        intervals_medians = intervals_medians[indices]
        intervals_means = intervals_means[indices]
        intervals_stds = intervals_stds[indices]
    
    # count all 13*5=65 features from here for every category according to timestamp
    
    # num_bids
    min_nbs, max_nbs, median_nbs, mean_nbs, std_nbs = descriptive_stats(num_bids)
    # rat_sim_bids
    min_rsb, max_rsb, median_rsb, mean_rsb, std_rsb = descriptive_stats(rat_sim_bids)
    # timeseries_mins
    min_mins_ts, max_mins_ts, median_mins_ts, mean_mins_ts, std_mins_ts = \
    descriptive_stats(series_mins)
    # timeseries_maxs
    min_maxs_ts, max_maxs_ts, median_maxs_ts, mean_maxs_ts, std_maxs_ts = \
    descriptive_stats(series_maxs)
    # timeseries_medians
    min_medians_ts, max_medians_ts, median_medians_ts, mean_medians_ts, std_medians_ts = \
    descriptive_stats(series_medians)
    # timeseries_means
    min_means_ts, max_means_ts, median_means_ts, mean_means_ts, std_means_ts = \
    descriptive_stats(series_means)
    # timeseries_stds
    min_stds_ts, max_stds_ts, median_stds_ts, mean_stds_ts, std_stds_ts = \
    descriptive_stats(series_stds)
    
    # num_periods
    min_nps, max_nps, median_nps, mean_nps, std_nps = descriptive_stats(num_periods)
    # intervals_mins
    min_mins_int, max_mins_int, median_mins_int, mean_mins_int, std_mins_int = \
    descriptive_stats(intervals_mins)
    # intervals_maxs
    min_maxs_int, max_maxs_int, median_maxs_int, mean_maxs_int, std_maxs_int = \
    descriptive_stats(intervals_maxs)
    # intervals_medians
    min_medians_int, max_medians_int, median_medians_int, mean_medians_int, std_medians_int = \
    descriptive_stats(intervals_medians)
    # intervals_means
    min_means_int, max_means_int, median_means_int, mean_means_int, std_means_int = \
    descriptive_stats(intervals_means)
    # intervals_stds
    min_stds_int, max_stds_int, median_stds_int, mean_stds_int, std_stds_int = \
    descriptive_stats(intervals_stds)

    return min_nbs, max_nbs, median_nbs, mean_nbs, std_nbs,\
            min_rsb, max_rsb, median_rsb, mean_rsb, std_rsb,\
            min_mins_ts, max_mins_ts, median_mins_ts, mean_mins_ts, std_mins_ts,\
            min_maxs_ts, max_maxs_ts, median_maxs_ts, mean_maxs_ts, std_maxs_ts,\
            min_medians_ts, max_medians_ts, median_medians_ts, mean_medians_ts, std_medians_ts,\
            min_means_ts, max_means_ts, median_means_ts, mean_means_ts, std_means_ts,\
            min_stds_ts, max_stds_ts, median_stds_ts, mean_stds_ts, std_stds_ts,\
            min_nps, max_nps, median_nps, mean_nps, std_nps,\
            min_mins_int, max_mins_int, median_mins_int, mean_mins_int, std_mins_int,\
            min_maxs_int, max_maxs_int, median_maxs_int, mean_maxs_int, std_maxs_int,\
            min_medians_int, max_medians_int, median_medians_int, mean_medians_int, std_medians_int,\
            min_means_int, max_means_int, median_means_int, mean_means_int, std_means_int,\
            min_stds_int, max_stds_int, median_stds_int, mean_stds_int, std_stds_int

Checking merchandise column¶

In addition to making timeseries features and adding features for the other dimensions, we will take a closer look into the merchandise column. If that is the case it means that it doesnt really help in identifying any pattern.

Closer look into the merchandise category¶

Something that could be interesting to see before dropping the category is how many humans/bots are in each category. For example if in a certain category (which is a bit unlikely given the definition for merchandise column) there are a lot of bots then maybe the "merchandise category" could be a simple feature that worth using. To be able to visualize i made a column_distributions function that takes a column name and outputs a dictionary in the form:

d = {'category': {'num_bidders': 0.0, 'perc_bots(%)': 0.0}, ... }

After this, the plot_stats_bar function is made to use the dictionary information. It plots a bar for each category; the number of bidders that have done bets and are also in the category are represented as the length of the bar and the percentage of bots in a category is represented by a color mapping - the more red a bar is, the more dominated this category is by bots.

import matplotlib.cm as cm
import matplotlib.colors as col

def plot_stats_bar(items_d, figure_width, title, y_max):
    """ Plots a bar chart of colored points from a dictionary of the form:
    {'category': {'num_bidders': 0.0, 'perc_bots(%)': 0.0},  ... } """

    # get the categories in dictionary
    values_categories = [item[0] for item in items_d]
    # get the number of bidders (bar height) of the dictionary categories
    values_num_bidders = [item[1]['num_bidders'] for item in items_d]
    # get the percentage of bots (color intensity) of the dictionary categories
    bot_percentages = [item[1]['perc_bots(%)']*1 for item in items_d]
    # initialize figure axes and indices
    fig, ax = plt.subplots()
    
    # adjust the size of the figure
    fig.set_figwidth(figure_width)
    fig.set_figheight(4)
    
    # set axes
    ax.set_title('{}'.format(title))
    ax.set_xlabel('categories')
    ax.set_ylabel('number of bidders')
    ax.set_ylim([0, y_max])
    # get the labels to rotate them
    labels = ax.get_xticklabels()
    # rotate
    plt.setp(labels, rotation=45, horizontalalignment='right')
    
    # This is  the colormap I'd like to use.
    cmap = cm.ScalarMappable(col.Normalize(0, 99), cmap=plt.get_cmap('Reds'))
    # Plot histogram.
    ax = plt.bar(values_categories, 
                 values_num_bidders, align='center', color=cmap.to_rgba(bot_percentages))
    # get the children
    for i, child in enumerate(ax.get_children()):
        # set the edgecolor for every bar
        child.set_edgecolor((0,0,0))
        
    plt.show()
    
def column_distributions(column_name):
    """ Accepts a categorical column of the data_bids table and finds its separate categories """
    # get merchandise categories
    categories = np.unique(data_bids[column_name])
    # get mask for '' country
    mask = np.isin(categories, list(control_set), invert=True)
    # remove ''
    categories = categories[mask]
    # make an empty internal dict for values
    cat_values = [{'num_bidders': None, 'perc_bots(%)': None} for x in range(categories.shape[0])]
    # initialize the dictionary to hold
    d = {k:v for (k,v) in zip(categories, cat_values)}

    for col, group in data_bids.groupby(column_name):
        
        if col=='' and column_name=='country':
            continue
            
        # get the unique bidder ids
        unique_bidders = np.unique(group['bidder_id'])
        # add the num_bidders for this merchandise
        d[col]['num_bidders'] = unique_bidders.shape[0]
        # find the counts of each outcome in the merchandise category
        counts = \

        # update dict
        d[col]['perc_bots(%)'] = counts_bots/np.sum(counts)*100

# style
plt.style.use('bmh')

def plot_counts(x, y, counts_of, column, set_log_x=False, set_log_y=False):
    """ Plots the counts of a column in a bar chart. """

    # init the figure and the axes object
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 1)
    # plot
    ax.bar(x, y, color='r', edgecolor='r')#, width=0.1
    # set text axes 1
    ax.set_title('Counts of {}s for observed numbers\n of {}'.format(column, counts_of))
    ax.set_xlabel('number of {}'.format(counts_of))
    ax.set_ylabel('counts of {}s'.format(column))
    ax.set_xscale('log') if set_log_x else None
    ax.set_yscale('log') if set_log_y else None
    # get the labels to rotate them
    labels = ax.get_xticklabels()
    # rotate
    plt.setp(labels, rotation=45, horizontalalignment='right')
    # show
    plt.show()

def describe_raw_categ_columns(column, counted_element):
    """ Aims to counts the values for bidders or bids (counted_element) of a column to 
    describe it with bar chart plots. """
    
    if counted_element=='bidders' or counted_element=='bids':
        pass
    else:
        raise ValueError("The counted element should be either bids or bidders.")
    
    # set an option to display some of the counts series
    pd.set_option('display.max_rows', 20)
    
    if counted_element=='bidders':
        # get the count of the unique bidder ids of the group
        num_counts_per_element = data_bids.groupby(column, sort=False)['bidder_id'].nunique()
    else:
        # get the count of all bids of the group -> the 'country' doesnt matter, just to render obj
        num_counts_per_element = data_bids.groupby(column, sort=False)['country'].count()
        
    if column=='country':
        column = 'countrie'
    
    # get the counts
    cc = pd.Series(num_counts_per_element).value_counts()
    
    # transform to dataframe
    cc = pd.DataFrame({'number of {}'.format(counted_element):np.array([float(x) for x in cc.index]),
                        'number of {}s'.format(column):cc.values})
    
    # sort the counts according to both columns
    cc.sort_values(['number of {}s'.format(column), 'number of {}'.format(counted_element)], 
                   ascending=[False, True], inplace=True)
    
    # set the index to properly reflect the iloc
    cc.set_index([list(range(cc.shape[0]))], inplace=True)

    print("Each count of {} is on the left and the {}s it appears in, on the right:\n\n{}\n"
          .format(counted_element, column, cc))

    # convert bidders or bids column to something easier to read and manipulate
    b = cc['number of {}'.format(counted_element)]
    # convert counts of the column element to something easier to read and manipulate
    counts = cc['number of {}s'.format(column)]
    
    if counted_element=='bidders':
        # plot counts for bidder ids
        plot_counts(b, counts, counted_element, column, set_log_x=False, set_log_y=True)
    else:
        # plot counts for bids
        plot_counts(b, counts, counted_element, column, set_log_x=True, set_log_y=True)

    print("The highest count of {} is {} and it appears in {} {}s."
          .format(counted_element, b.iloc[-1], counts.iloc[-1], column))
    print("The lowest count of {} is {} and it appears in {} {}s."
          .format(counted_element, b.iloc[0], counts.iloc[0], column))
    print("{} of the {} {}s (which is {:.2f}%) have {} {} or less."
          .format(counts[:10].sum(), counts.sum(), column, counts[:10].sum()/counts.sum()*100,
                  b.iloc[9], counted_element))
    print("\n")

from scipy.stats import gaussian_kde

def plot_outcome_area_with_num_of_elements(column, x_max=0):
    """ Plots an area for the two groups of outcomes and a category absolute numbers. """
    
    # bidders 0
    bidders_0 = data_bidders[['bidder_id', 'outcome']][data_bidders['outcome']==0]
    # bidders 1
    bidders_1 = data_bidders[['bidder_id', 'outcome']][data_bidders['outcome']==1]
    
    # init number of auctions column for humans
    bidders_0['num_auctions'] = np.nan
    # init number of auctions column for bots
    bidders_1['num_auctions'] = np.nan
    
    for bidder, group in data_bids.groupby('bidder_id'):
        
        if bidder in bidders_1['bidder_id'].values:
            bidders_1.loc[bidders_1['bidder_id']==bidder, 'num_auctions'] = group[column].nunique()
        else:
            bidders_0.loc[bidders_0['bidder_id']==bidder, 'num_auctions'] = group[column].nunique()
    
    # sort the counts according to both columns
    bidders_1.sort_values('num_auctions', ascending=True, inplace=True)
    # sort the counts according to both columns
    bidders_0.sort_values('num_auctions', ascending=True, inplace=True)
    
    # reset the index
    bidders_0.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)
    # reset the index
    bidders_1.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)
    
    # set the magnitude for x dimension of the plot
    xs_max = data_bids[column].nunique() if x_max==0 else x_max
    
    density_0 = gaussian_kde(bidders_0['num_auctions'])
    xs_0 = np.linspace(0, xs_max, 2000)
    density_0.covariance_factor = lambda : .25
    density_0._compute_covariance()
    
    density_1 = gaussian_kde(bidders_1['num_auctions'])
    xs_1 = np.linspace(0, xs_max, 2000)
    density_1.covariance_factor = lambda : .25
    density_1._compute_covariance()

    print("Here is the Probability Density Function plot the bot/human groups of '{}' category:"
          .format(column))
    
    if column=='country':
        column = 'countrie'

    # init the figure and the axes object
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 1)
    
    # plot
    ax.fill_between(xs_0, density_0(xs_0), color='green', lw=2, alpha=0.5, edgecolor='b')
    ax.fill_between(xs_1, density_1(xs_1), color='red', lw=2, alpha=0.5, edgecolor='b')
    ax.set_facecolor((1, 1, 1))
    # set text axes 1
    ax.set_title('PDFs for number of {}s to outcomes'.format(column))
    ax.set_xlabel('{}s count'.format(column))
    ax.set_ylabel('bidder probability')
    ax.legend(['humans', 'bots'])
    # get the labels to rotate them
    labels = ax.get_xticklabels()
    # rotate
    plt.setp(labels, rotation=45, horizontalalignment='right')
    # show
    plt.show()

List of countries with a few bids¶

In addition to visuals, something that could help in making features from the countries column could be the number of small countries someone is making bids from. That is because we see that the countries that have the least bids are more "contaminated". In order to decide how many bids is low enough to put a country in the list, we considered two ways of doing it. The first one would be to look at the graphs and it seems that lower than 5 bids would maybe be the best number.

However this way we are leaking our knowledge of the data set too much into the model and it will for sure not generalize well. This would be a useless feature for example if we were building a model for the auctions platform and the bidding builds up and eventually there is no country with less than 5 bids. For that reason, as low activity countries we will consider the countries in the 1st Quartile in the distribution of numbers of bids.

In [32]:
np.set_printoptions(threshold=100)

percentile = 25

def elements_with_low_bidders(data_bids, column, percentile=0, find_ones=False, highest_count=0):
    """ Finds the elements with low bidders """

    # get the series with country as index and the unique values count as value
    num_bidders_per_element = data_bids.groupby(column, sort=False)['bidder_id'].nunique()
    
    if percentile:
        
        # find the low threshold according to the first quartile
        low_threshold = np.percentile(num_bidders_per_element, percentile)

        # slice the list according to the low threshold
        countries_with_low_bidders = num_bidders_per_element[num_bidders_per_element<low_threshold]
        
    elif find_ones:
        
        # slice the list according to the low threshold
        countries_with_low_bidders = num_bidders_per_element[num_bidders_per_element==1]
        
    elif highest_count:
        
        # slice the list according to the low threshold
        countries_with_low_bidders = num_bidders_per_element[num_bidders_per_element<=highest_count]
        
    else:
        
        raise AttributeError("Need to specify either one of the attributes: percentile, \
find_ones, highest_count")
        
    return countries_with_low_bidders.shape[0], np.array(countries_with_low_bidders.index.tolist())

# apply the function for countries
num_countries_with_low_bidders, countries_with_low_bidders = \
                    elements_with_low_bidders(data_bids, 'country', percentile=percentile)

print("The {} countries with low bidders (below {}th percentile) are:\n{}"
      .format(num_countries_with_low_bidders, percentile, countries_with_low_bidders))

Features according to countries¶

First of all the country column can be used as a grouper when making features for time per bidder. The time patters of a bidder according to the country might be very telling on whether a user is a bot or human. In this group of features, the number of bids per country, the response times and other relevant things are considered.

Besides those, we will use some features that refer to the counts of countries. For example if a bidder makes bids from many countries, if we count how many bids are for each country we have a distribution of counts. Out of this distribution we can extract the following statistics:

  • The number of countries the user is making bids from,
  • the number of countries with few bidders (e.g. less than the 1st quartile) a bidder bids from,
  • the count of the most used country relative to the count of all countries,
  • the count of the least used country relative the the count of all countries,
  • the mean count of countries,
  • the median count of countries and,
  • the std of the country counts
In [33]:
def features_countries(series, low_bidder_countries,  num_countries_low):
    """ Produces the features that have to do with countries for a single bidder_id. """
    
    # get the counts
    counts = series.value_counts()
    # do stats
    counts_n = counts.shape[0]
    # number of countries with few bidders (normalized)
    counts_n_small = np.intersect1d(counts.index.values,
                                    low_bidder_countries).shape[0] / num_countries_low
    max_count = np.max(counts.values)
    min_count = np.min(counts.values)
    mean_count = np.mean(counts.values)
    median_count = np.median(counts.values)
    std_count = np.std(counts.values)    
        
    return counts_n, counts_n_small, max_count, min_count, mean_count, median_count, std_count

def features_auctions(series):
    """ Produces the features that have to do with auctions for a single bidder_id. """
    
    # get the counts
    counts = series.value_counts()
    # do stats
    counts_n = counts.shape[0]
    max_count = np.max(counts.values)
    min_count = np.min(counts.values)
    mean_count = np.mean(counts.values)
    median_count = np.median(counts.values)
    std_count = np.std(counts.values)    
        
    return counts_n, max_count, min_count, mean_count, median_count, std_count

Features according to urls¶

When making features for urls, it is needed for the picture shown from the above plots to be taken into account. Probably urls can give us a simple and powerful feature which is the count of urls for each bidder. That is because we saw that the common place is that one url is usually connected with a bidder or a bid. When the count of bids, is ridiculusly high that is probably alarming, but that is not the case with the count of bidders.

On the contrary because the count of bidders was high at some points we might think that the url data might not be documented well or there might be something we don't know for the website. It might be the case that the personal data are being extracted by the cookie and the url is standardized, given that this is how cookies work with urls etc.

An additional thing, looking at the grand scale of the dataset, there are around 3m bids and 663k urls which means that the user is not doing too many things with one url, as it burns out to a few bids. There is not much to the users behavior with it. That is the main reason for i will not use the timeseries features with them. Instead the features i will use will be:

  • The number of different urls someone has bid from, normalized by the number of all urls (number of all the bidders bids),
  • the count of the most used url relative to the count of all urls,
  • the count of the least used url relative the the count of all urls,
  • the mean count of urls,
  • the median count of urls and,
  • the std of the url counts

Interpretation: Similarly to the ips, we can see here that around 90% of the ips are mapped 1 to 1 with the bidders. Also, there are probably more than 10k cases where several ips are shared with multiple bidders. That is a bit strange since it means that in a good amount of the bidderbase, an ip is shared by multiple people, and while it is something that can for sure happen as people share internet etc it seems a bit too frequent here.

Also in terms of bids, it seems that something similar happens. While the majority of the ips are for a specific bid, there are many others that are shared. Also there are many cases where a specific ip is used for a lot of bids, but that is not very strange since there might be public areas where people do bid from. That is confirmed from the PDF of the counts as the probability of a bidder that is a bot to have a big number of ips is small relative to the human one.

Features according to ips¶

Similar to urls, the picture painted by these plots is that by large ips are mapped to a single user. However, there are more cases in ips than the urls where ips have been used by more than one person, which is logical to an extend. Also there are more cases where something is being used by multiple people which also makes sense since urls are more personalized to a specific bidder account.

Regarding the features, once again we will not use the timeseries features with the ips. That is because, even more than the urls, there are 1m ips and 3m bids, which means that in most cases there is hardly any time for a behavioral pattern to be captured and prove meaningful. Instead, we will use:

  • The number of different ips someone has bid from, normalized by the number of all ips (number of all the bidders bids),
  • the count of the most used ip relative to the count of all ips,
  • the count of the least used ip relative the the count of all ips,
  • the mean count of ips,
  • the median count of ips and,
  • the std of the counts
In [45]:
def features_ips(series):
    """ Produces the features that have to do with ips for a single bidder_id. """ 
    
    # get the count
    counts = series.value_counts()
    # do stats
    counts_n = counts.shape[0]
    max_count = np.max(counts.values)
    min_count = np.min(counts.values)
    mean_count = np.mean(counts.values)
    median_count = np.median(counts.values)
    std_count = np.std(counts.values)    
    
    return counts_n, max_count, min_count, mean_count, median_count, std_count

Feature Production¶

The features i will use for this project will be all the features that were made specifically for the separate columns which are:

  • The 13 timeseries features for of 'time' column
  • the 7 features for 'country' category
  • the 6 features for each of the 'auction', 'device', 'url', 'ip' columns (24 features in total),
  • and the 65 features created for the timeseries of 'auction' column *

*The reason we did not use the extra timeseries features for 'country', 'device', 'url', 'ip' is that by trial and error we saw that 'auction' is the category that yields the best results and that we want to keep the dimensionality to a reasonable number
